    pearls: ["L. crispatus dominance (CST-I) is the most protective vaginal community state  -  produces high levels of D-lactic acid, hydrogen peroxide, and bacteriocins", "Gardnerella biofilm is the key driver of BV recurrence  -  standard antibiotic therapy reduces planktonic bacteria but biofilm persists in up to 50% of cases", "Non-albicans Candida (especially C. glabrata) should be suspected in recurrent VVC unresponsive to azoles  -  culture with species identification and susceptibility testing is essential", "Trichomoniasis is associated with 2-fold increased risk of HIV acquisition due to epithelial disruption and inflammatory cell recruitment", "BV in pregnancy is associated with preterm birth, PPROM, and low birth weight  -  screening and treatment recommended in symptomatic pregnant women", "Boric acid 600 mg vaginal suppositories are first-line for non-albicans VVC and an effective adjunct for recurrent BV  -  toxic if ingested orally, so counsel patients carefully"],
    quiz: [
      { question: "A woman with her fourth episode of vulvovaginal candidiasis this year fails to respond to fluconazole. Culture grows Candida glabrata. What is the most appropriate treatment?", options: ["Increase fluconazole dose to 400 mg daily for 14 days", "Prescribe boric acid 600 mg vaginal suppository daily for 14-21 days", "Prescribe metronidazole 500 mg PO BID for 7 days", "Prescribe clotrimazole cream for 3 days"], correct: 1, rationale: "C. glabrata has intrinsic reduced susceptibility to azole antifungals due to upregulation of CDR efflux pumps and ERG11 mutations. Higher fluconazole doses are unlikely to be effective. Boric acid 600 mg vaginal suppository for 14-21 days is the recommended first-line treatment for non-albicans VVC. It disrupts fungal biofilm and cell membrane integrity through a mechanism distinct from azoles." },
      { question: "What molecular mechanism explains the high recurrence rate of bacterial vaginosis after metronidazole treatment?", options: ["Metronidazole resistance mutations in Gardnerella vaginalis", "Gardnerella biofilm on vaginal epithelium persists after antibiotic therapy and serves as a reservoir for reinfection", "Rapid re-acquisition of BV-associated bacteria from sexual partners", "Metronidazole depletes Lactobacillus, preventing microbiome restoration"], correct: 1, rationale: "Gardnerella vaginalis forms a structured polymicrobial biofilm on vaginal epithelium that is resistant to antibiotic penetration. While metronidazole effectively kills planktonic (free-floating) bacteria, the biofilm persists in up to 50% of treated patients. This biofilm serves as a reservoir for bacterial regrowth once antibiotic pressure is removed, driving the 50-80% recurrence rate within 12 months." }
    ]
